                        "death and reassemble randomly. Against all of these, Paul insists on transformation rather "
                        "than escape. The seed analogy (15:36-38) was a common philosophical illustration: the "
                        "Stoics used the seed to argue for the logos spermatikos (seminal reason) embedded in matter. "
                        "But Paul uses it differently: the seed dies, and God gives it a new body -- not merely "
                        "different in form but categorically upgraded. The distinction between celestial and "
                        "terrestrial glory (15:40-41) draws on the Jewish tradition that heavenly beings possess a "
